      • attemptMergeIn

        <TAdd,TCur> RepositoryCompilerStates.RTermination<TVal,java.lang.Throwable,RepositoryCompilerStates.RFlow<TVal,TCur,?>> attemptMergeIn(Supplier<TAdd> supplier,
                                                                                                                                       Merger<? super TPre,? super TAdd,Result<TCur>> attemptMerger)
        Description copied from interface: RepositoryCompilerStates.RSyncFlow
        Like RepositoryCompilerStates.RSyncFlow.mergeIn(com.google.android.agera.Supplier<TAdd>, com.google.android.agera.Merger<? super TPre, ? super TAdd, TCur>), take the input value and the value newly obtained from the given supplier, and attempt to merge them using the given merger. If the attempt fails, terminate the data processing flow by sending the failure to the termination clause that follows; otherwise take the successful value as the output of this directive.

        This method is agnostic of the return type of the supplier. If it itself is fallible, the merger is held responsible for processing the failure, which may choose to pass the failure on as the result of the merge.

        Specified by:

      • goTo

        TSelf goTo(java.util.concurrent.Executor executor)
        Go to the given executor to continue the data processing flow. The executor is assumed to never throw RejectedExecutionException. Synchronous executors are supported but the risk of stack overflow will be higher. Note that when the executor resumes the flow, the directives that follow are run sequentially within the same Runnable.run() call, until the flow completes or the next goTo() or, if applicable, goLazy() directive is reached. Depending on the directives and operators used, this may starve the executor. If necessary, use additional goTo() directives with the same executor to achieve fairness.

      • goLazy

        RepositoryCompilerStates.RSyncFlow<TVal,TPre,?> goLazy()
        Suspend the data processing flow and notify the registered Updatables of updates. The remaining of the flow will be run synchronously and uninterruptibly the first time Supplier.get() is called, to produce the new repository value lazily. After this directive, goTo(Executor) is no longer available, and all further operators should be fairly lightweight in order not to block the callers of get() for too long.
